{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585248"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14941"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14941"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.09,0.02,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7629"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14941"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51880"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"9961"},{"type":"tags","id":"10921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18663"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESome pathogenic microorganisms have evolved mechanisms to survive inside phagocytic cells, which normally function to destroy invading organisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following microorganisms can avoid destruction by inhibiting fusion of the phagosome and lysosome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Staphylococcus aureus","Escherichia coli","Neisseria meningitidis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ability to survive inside phagocytes by preventing phagolysosomal fusion is a key virulence mechanism for certain intracellular pathogens. \u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a classic example of an organism that employs this strategy. \u003Cem\u003EM. tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E uses multiple mechanisms including prevention of phagosome acidification and interference with trafficking proteins to avoid destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E is an extracellular pathogen that does not typically survive inside phagocytes. It uses other virulence mechanisms such as capsule formation and toxin production.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E has different survival strategies. While it can survive briefly inside phagocytes, it does not specifically inhibit phagolysosomal fusion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E is typically destroyed by normal phagolysosomal function and does not have mechanisms to prevent this fusion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily an extracellular pathogen that uses capsules and other mechanisms to avoid phagocytosis entirely rather than surviving within phagocytes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mycobacterium tuberculosis can survive inside phagocytes by preventing phagolysosomal fusion.","This intracellular survival mechanism is a key virulence factor that allows these pathogens to evade host immune responses.","Understanding bacterial survival mechanisms helps inform therapeutic approaches targeting these pathogens."],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Deretic V, Singh S, Master S, Harris J, Roberts E, Kyei G, Davis A, de Haro S, Naylor J, Lee HH, Vergne I. Mycobacterium tuberculosis inhibition of phagolysosome biogenesis and autophagy as a host defence mechanism. Cell Microbiol. 2006 May;8(5):719-27. doi: 10.1111/j.1462-5822.2006.00705.x. PMID: 16611222.","Grygiel-G\u00f3rniak B, Folga BA. Chlamydia trachomatis-An Emerging Old Entity? Microorganisms. 2023 May 14;11(5):1283. doi: 10.3390/microorganisms11051283. PMID: 37317257; PMCID: PMC10221348."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14941"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51880"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T09:00:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T09:01:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7629"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66429"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo